      <body>I don't think it's the responsibility of Rails validations to make sure that the validations you've defined map to actual database fields. Your validations are model (behavior) logic, not persistence logic. Moreover, you may indeed want to have validations on model attributes that don't exist in the database. In my opinion, this is the correct behavior, not a bug.</body>
      <body-html>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;I don't think it's the responsibility of Rails validations to
make sure that the validations you've defined map to actual
database fields. Your validations are model (behavior) logic, not
persistence logic. Moreover, you may indeed want to have
validations on model attributes that don't exist in the database.
In my opinion, this is the correct behavior, not a bug.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</body-html>
